{"title_page": "Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor\n|image_name      = Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor logo.png\n|caption         = Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor logo\n|image_size      = \n|latin_name      = \n|tagline         = \n|type            = [[Further education]] college\n|principal       = Aled Jones-Griffith\n|city            = [[North Wales]]\n|province        = [[Wales]]\n|country         = [[United Kingdom]]\n|address         = {{lang|cy|Ffordd Ty\u2019n y Coed, Dolgellau, LL40 2SW|italic=no}}\n|campus          = Dolgellau, Glynllifon, Pwllheli\n|free_label      = \n|free            = \n|sports          = \n|colours         = \n|nickname        = \n|mascot          = \n|affiliations    = \n|website         = {{Official URL}}\n|logo            = \n|footnotes       = \n}}\n[[File:MygColMeir.jpg|left|thumb|Mug bearing the college coat of arms]]\n{{coord|52.745|-3.898|display=title|region:GB_scale:5000}}\n[[File:Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor. - geograph.org.uk - 247302.jpg|right|thumb|{{lang|cy|Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor|italic=no}}]]\n'''{{lang|cy|Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor|italic=no}}''' (meaning in English \"Meirion-Dwyfor College\"), also known as '''CMD''', is a college in {{lang|cy|[[Gwynedd]]|italic=no}}, Wales with its main campus in {{lang|cy|[[Dolgellau]]|italic=no}}. It serves the areas of {{lang|cy|[[Meirionydd]]|italic=no}} and {{lang|cy|[[Dwyfor]]|italic=no}}. It has a [[bilingual]] [[language policy]] and offers the opportunity to study most subjects through the medium of [[Welsh language|Welsh]]. Since 1 April 2012, it has been a constituent college of {{lang|cy|[[Gr\u0175p Llandrillo Menai]]|italic=no}}.\n\n{{lang|cy|Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor|italic=no}} has three main campuses at {{lang|cy|Dolgellau|italic=no}} in {{lang|cy|Meirionnydd|italic=no}}, {{lang|cy|[[Pwllheli]]|italic=no}} in {{lang|cy|Dwyfor|italic=no}} and {{lang|cy|[[Glynllifon]]|italic=no}} (for agricultural courses) near {{lang|cy|[[Caernarfon]]|italic=no}}.  The {{lang|cy|Dolgellau|italic=no}} campus was previously occupied by [[Dr Williams School]].\n\nNotable former pupils include the singer [[Duffy (singer)|Duffy]], who was elected president of the Students' union.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northwest/halloffame/showbiz/duffy.shtml |title=BBC North East Wales Hall of Fame |publisher=BBC |accessdate=16 September 2009 }}</ref>\n\n{{lang|cy|Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor|italic=no}} formally merged with {{lang|cy|[[Coleg Llandrillo]]|italic=no}} on 1 April 2010; this new college merged with {{lang|cy|[[Coleg Menai]]|italic=no}} in 2012 to form {{lang|cy|[[Gr\u0175p Llandrillo Menai]]|italic=no}}. The merged organisation is one of the largest further education colleges in the UK. Although the colleges have merged their management and have a central administration, the {{lang|cy|Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor|italic=no}} campuses retain the {{lang|cy|Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor|italic=no}} name.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.gllm.ac.uk/ Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor - Grwp Llandrillo Menai]\n\n{{Universities and colleges in Wales}}\n{{Gwynedd}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Dolgellau]]\n[[Category:Llandwrog]]\n[[Category:Pwllheli]]\n[[Category:Further education colleges in Gwynedd]]\n[[Category:Further education colleges in Snowdonia]]\n\n\n{{Wales-school-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor\n|image_name      = Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor logo.png\n|caption         = Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor logo\n|image_size      = \n|latin_name      = \n|tagline         = \n|type            = [[Further education]] college\n|principal       = Linda Wyn\n|staff           = \n|students        = 22,000\n|city            = [[North Wales]]\n|province        = [[Wales]]\n|country         = [[United Kingdom]]\n|address         = {{lang|cy|Ffordd Ty\u2019n y Coed, Dolgellau, LL40 2SW|italic=no}}\n|campus          = [http://www.gllm.ac.uk/meirion-dwyfor/dolgellau Dolgellau], [http://www.gllm.ac.uk/meirion-dwyfor/glynllifon Glynllifon], [http://www.gllm.ac.uk/meirion-dwyfor/pwllheli Pwllheli]\n|free_label      = \n|free            = \n|sports          = \n|colours         = \n|nickname        = \n|mascot          = \n|affiliations    = \n|website         = {{Official URL}}\n|logo            = \n|footnotes       = \n}}\n[[File:MygColMeir.jpg|left|thumb|Mug bearing the college coat of arms]]\n{{coord|52.745|-3.898|display=title|region:GB_scale:5000}}\n[[File:Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor. - geograph.org.uk - 247302.jpg|right|thumb|{{lang|cy|Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor|italic=no}}]]\n'''{{lang|cy|Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor|italic=no}}''' (meaning in English \"Meirion-Dwyfor College\"), also known as '''CMD''', is a college in {{lang|cy|[[Gwynedd]]|italic=no}}, Wales with its main campus in {{lang|cy|[[Dolgellau]]|italic=no}}. It serves the areas of {{lang|cy|[[Meirionydd]]|italic=no}} and {{lang|cy|[[Dwyfor]]|italic=no}}. It has a [[bilingual]] [[language policy]] and offers the opportunity to study most subjects through the medium of [[Welsh language|Welsh]]. Since 1 April 2012, it has been a constituent college of {{lang|cy|[[Gr\u0175p Llandrillo Menai]]|italic=no}}.\n\n{{lang|cy|Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor|italic=no}} has three main campuses at {{lang|cy|Dolgellau|italic=no}} in {{lang|cy|Meirionnydd|italic=no}}, {{lang|cy|[[Pwllheli]]|italic=no}} in {{lang|cy|Dwyfor|italic=no}} and {{lang|cy|[[Glynllifon]]|italic=no}} (for agricultural courses) near {{lang|cy|[[Caernarfon]]|italic=no}}.  The {{lang|cy|Dolgellau|italic=no}} campus was previously occupied by [[Dr Williams School]].\n\nNotable former pupils include the singer [[Duffy (singer)|Duffy]], who was elected president of the Students' union.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northwest/halloffame/showbiz/duffy.shtml |title=BBC North East Wales Hall of Fame |publisher=BBC |accessdate=16 September 2009 }}</ref>\n\n{{lang|cy|Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor|italic=no}} formally merged with {{lang|cy|[[Coleg Llandrillo]]|italic=no}} on 1 April 2010; this new college merged with {{lang|cy|[[Coleg Menai]]|italic=no}} in 2012 to form {{lang|cy|[[Gr\u0175p Llandrillo Menai]]|italic=no}}. The merged organisation is one of the largest further education colleges in the UK, located at twelve campuses across four counties. Although the colleges have merged their management and have a central administration, the {{lang|cy|Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor|italic=no}} campuses retain the {{lang|cy|Coleg Meirion-Dwyfor|italic=no}} name.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gllm.ac.uk/meirion-dwyfor College website]\n\n{{Universities and colleges in Wales}}\n{{Gwynedd}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Dolgellau]]\n[[Category:Llandwrog]]\n[[Category:Pwllheli]]\n[[Category:Further education colleges in Gwynedd]]\n[[Category:Further education colleges in Snowdonia]]\n\n\n{{Wales-school-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Webdewi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coleg_Meirion-Dwyfor"}
{"title_page": "List of socialist states", "text_new": "{{short description|List of self-declared socialist states}}\n{{about|self-proclaimed socialist states|countries governed by Marxist\u2013Leninist communist parties|Communist state|constitutional references to socialism in multi-party democracies|Socialism in liberal democratic constitutions|countries constitutionally committed to socialism|Socialist state}}\n{{socialism sidebar}}\nSeveral past and present [[State (polity)|states]] have declared themselves [[socialist state]]s or in the process of building [[socialism]]. The majority of self-declared socialist countries have been [[Marxist\u2013Leninist]] or inspired by it, following the model of the [[Soviet Union]] or some form of [[People's democracy (Marxism\u2013Leninism)|people's]] or [[National democracy (Marxism\u2013Leninism)|national democracy]]. They share a common definition of socialism and they refer to themselves as socialist states on the road to [[communism]] with a leading [[vanguard party]] structure, hence they are called [[communist states]]. Meanwhile, the countries in the non-Marxist\u2013Leninist category represent a wide variety of different interpretations of the term socialism and in many cases the countries do not define what they mean by it. Modern uses of the term socialism are wide in meaning and interpretation.\n\nAs a [[sovereign state]] is a different entity from the [[political party]] that rules that state at any given time, a country may be ruled by a [[socialist party]] without the country itself claiming to be socialist, occurring in both [[One-party state|one-party]] and [[Multi-party system|multi-party]] political systems. In particular, there are numerous cases of [[social democratic]] and [[democratic socialist]] parties winning elections in [[liberal democratic]] states and ruling for a number of [[Term of office|terms]] until a different party wins the elections. While socialist parties won many elections around the world and most elections in the [[Nordic countries]], they did not adopt socialism as the [[state ideology]].\n\nSeveral countries with [[Socialism in liberal democratic constitutions|liberal democratic constitutions]] mention socialism. [[India]] is a liberal democracy that has been ruled by non-socialist parties on many occasions, but its [[Constitution of India|constitution]] makes references to socialism. Certain other countries such as [[Croatia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.servat.unibe.ch/icl/hr00000_.html|title=Croatia Constitution|last=Tschentscher|first=Axel|website=Servat.unibe.ch|accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref> [[Hungary]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.servat.unibe.ch/icl/hu__indx.html|title=Hungary Index|last=Tschentscher|first=Axel|website=Servat.unibe.ch|accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref> [[Myanmar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.constituteproject.org/constitution/Myanmar_2008|title=Myanmar 2008|publisher=Constitute Project|accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref> and [[Poland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.servat.unibe.ch/icl/pl00000_.html|title=Poland - Constitution|last=Tschentscher|first=Axel|website=Servat.unibe.ch|accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref> have constitutions that make references to their communist and socialist past by recognizing or condemning it, but without claiming to be socialist in the present.\n\n== Overview ==\n[[Self-identification]] is the only criterion used by the list, therefore it includes all countries that have claimed to be [[socialist]], even if their claims are disputed. All countries that have not claimed to be socialist are excluded, even in cases where certain outside observers regarded those countries as socialist. This list includes countries that assert in their [[constitution]]s that they are based on socialism, regardless of their economic or political system.<!-- As for countries with no written constitution... --> It does not list countries that do not have [[constitutional references to socialism]] as [[socialist state]]s, even in cases where the government is currently run by a [[socialist party]] or other [[left-wing]] ([[centre-left]] and [[far-left]]) parties. On the other hand, countries that do maintain constitutional references to socialism are listed, even when those countries are ruled by non-socialist parties. As a result, this list is best understood as a list of countries that explicitly claim to be socialist and it does not reflect the actual economic systems themselves. The following images are a combined map of all countries that declared themselves socialist states under any definition at some point in their history, color-coded for the number of years they said they were socialist and by Soviet sources:\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = center\n| image1 = Socialist states by duration.png\n| width1 = 565\n| caption1 = Map of socialist states by duration\n{{legend|#FF0000|Over 70 years}}\n{{legend|#FF6600|60\u201370 years}}\n{{legend|#B0B000|50\u201360 years}}\n{{legend|#00CC00|40\u201350 years}}\n{{legend|#0000FF|30\u201340 years}}\n{{legend|#000033|20\u201330 years}}\n{{legend|#9966FF|Under 20 years}}\n| image2 = Communist Block.svg\n| width2 = 497\n| caption2 = Note that not all of the bright red states remained [[Soviet allies]]\n{{legend|#E00202|States that had [[communist government]]s}}\n{{legend|#DB5502|States that the [[Soviet Union]] believed at one point to be [[moving toward socialism]]}}\n{{legend|#D4CE26|Other [[socialist state]]s}}\n}}\n\n== Current socialist states ==\n=== Marxist\u2013Leninist states ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=100%\n!width=150px|Country\n!width=85px|Since\n!width=85px|Duration\n!width=100px|Form of government\n!width=95px|Party\n!width=95px|Head of party\n!width=95px|Head of state\n!width=95px|Head of government\n|-\n|{{flag|China|name=People's Republic of China}}{{refn|[[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] are administrated under the \"[[One country, two systems]]\" principle. For an overview of the princple, see [http://www.china.org.cn/english/features/dengxiaoping/103372.htm \"One Country, Two Systems\"].|group=\"nb\"}}\n|1 October 1949\n|{{ayd|1949|10|1}}\n|[[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[One-party state|one-party]]<br />[[socialist republic]]\n|[[Communist Party of China]]\n|align=\"center\" colspan=\"2\"|[[Xi Jinping]]<br />(since 2012)\n|align=\"center\"|[[Li Keqiang]]<br />(since 2012)\n|-\n|{{flag|Cuba|name=Republic of Cuba}}\n|1 January 1959\n|{{ayd|1959|1|1}}\n|[[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[One-party state|one-party]]<br />[[socialist republic]]\n|[[Communist Party of Cuba]]\n|align=\"center\"|[[Ra\u00fal Castro]]<br />(since 2011)\n|align=\"center\"|[[Miguel D\u00edaz-Canel]]<br />(since 2018)\n|align=\"center\"|[[Manuel Marrero Cruz]]<br />(since 2019)\n|-\n|{{flag|Laos|name=Lao People's Democratic Republic}}\n|2 December 1975\n|{{ayd|1975|12|2}}\n|[[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[One-party state|one-party]]<br />[[socialist republic]]\n|[[Lao People's Revolutionary Party]]\n|align=\"center\" colspan=\"2\"|[[Bounnhang Vorachith]]<br />(since 2016)\n|align=\"center\"|[[Thongloun Sisoulith]]<br />(since 2016)\n|-\n|{{flag|Vietnam|name=Socialist Republic of Vietnam}}\n|2 September 1945\n|{{ayd|1945|9|2}}\n|[[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[One-party state|one-party]]<br />[[socialist republic]]\n|[[Communist Party of Vietnam]]\n|align=\"center\"|[[Nguy\u1ec5n Ph\u00fa Tr\u1ecdng]]<br />(since 2011)\n|align=\"center\"|Nguy\u1ec5n Ph\u00fa Tr\u1ecdng<br />(since 2018)\n|align=\"center\"|[[Nguy\u1ec5n Xu\u00e2n Ph\u00fac]]<br />(since 2016)\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Non-Marxist\u2013Leninist states ===\n==== Current countries with constitutional references to socialism ====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Country\n!scope=\"col\"|Since\n!scope=\"col\"|Duration\n!scope=\"col\"|Form of government\n!scope=\"col\" width=340|Constitutional statement\n|-\n|{{flag|Algeria|name=People's Democratic Republic of Algeria}}\n|28 November 1996\n|{{ayd|1996|11|28}}\n|[[Multi-party system|Multi-party]] [[semi-presidential republic]]\n|Preamble: \"Gathered in the national movement and later within the National Front of Liberation, the Algerian people have made great sacrifices in order to assume their collective destiny in the framework of recovered freedom and cultural identity and to build authentic people's democratic constitutional institutions. The National Front of Liberation crowned the sacrifices of the best sons of Algeria during the people's war of liberation with independence and built a modern and full sovereign State\".<ref>{{cite web|title=THE Constitution of the People's Democratic Republic of Algeriah|url=http://www.servat.unibe.ch/icl/ag00000_.html|publisher=Embassy of Algeria London|date=28 November 1996|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref><br /><br />The [[National Liberation Front (Algeria)|National Front of Liberation]] is a political party based on [[Arab socialism]].<ref name=ANger>Evans, M. (2007). Algeria\u202f: Anger of the Dispossessed. London: Yale University Press. p. 34</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Bangladesh|name=People's Republic of Bangladesh}}\n|11 April 1971\n|{{ayd|1971|4|11}}\n|[[Multi-party system|Multi-party]] [[parliamentary republic]]\n|align=\"left\"|Preamble: \"Further pledging that it shall be a fundamental aim of the State to realise through the democratic process, a socialist society free from exploitation, a society in which the rule of law, fundamental human rights and freedoms, equality and justice, political, economic and social, will be secured for all citizens\".<ref>{{cite constitution|article=Preamble|section=Preamble|country=the People's Republic of Bangladesh|language=|ratified=4 November 1972|url=http://www1.umn.edu/humanrts/research/bangladesh-constitution.pdf|accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Guyana|name=Co-operative Republic of Guyana}}\n|6 October 1980\n|{{ayd|1980|10|6}}\n|[[Multi-party system|Multi-party]] [[presidential republic]]\n|Section 1, Article 1: \"Guyana is an indivisible, secular, democratic sovereign state in the course of transition from capitalism to socialism and shall be known as the Co-operative Republic of Guyana\".<ref>{{cite constitution|article=1|section=The State and the Constitution|country=the Cooperative Republic of Guyana|language=|ratified=20 February 1980|url=http://parliament.gov.gy/constitution.pdf|accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|India|name=Republic of India}}\n|18 December 1976<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiacode.nic.in/coiweb/amend/amend42.htm|title=The Constitution (Forty-second Amendment) Act, 1976|publisher=India Code|access-date=14 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328040620/http://indiacode.nic.in/coiweb/amend/amend42.htm|archive-date=28 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|{{ayd|1976|12|18}}\n|[[Multi-party system|Multi-party]] [[parliamentary republic]]\n|Preamble: \"We, the people of India, having solemnly resolved to constitute India into a Sovereign Socialist Secular Democratic Republic and to secure to all its citizens\".<ref>{{cite constitution|article=Preamble|section=Preamble|country=the Republic of India|language=|ratified=26 November 1949|url=http://lawmin.nic.in/coi/coiason29july08.pdf|accessdate=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909230437/http://lawmin.nic.in/coi/coiason29july08.pdf|archivedate=9 September 2014|df=}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|North Korea}} [[North Korea|Democratic People's Republic of Korea]]\n|19 February 1992 \n|{{ayd|1992|2|19}}\n|[[One-party state|One-party]] [[socialist republic]]\n|Preamble: \"The Democratic People's Republic of Korea is the socialist motherland of ''[[Juche]]'', which has applied the ideas and leadership of [[Kim Il-sung]]\".<ref>{{cite constitution|article=Preamble|section=Preamble|country=the Democratic People's Republic of Korea|language=|ratified=9 September 1948|url=http://www.servat.unibe.ch/icl/kn00000_.html|accessdate=}}</ref><br /><br />Formerly a Marxist\u2013Leninist state.{{refn|Although the government's official state ideology now incorporates the ''[[Juche]]'' element of [[Kim Il-sung]]'s [[Kimilsungism\u2013Kimjongilism]] policy as opposed to orthodox [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]], North Korea still considers itself a socialist state.<ref>Article Preamble, Section Preamble of the [[Socialist Constitution of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea]] (27 December 1972). \"The Democratic People's Republic of Korea is the socialist motherland of ''[[Juche]]'', which has applied the ideas and leadership of [[Kim Il-sung]]\".</ref>|group=\"nb\"}}\n|-\n|{{flag|Nepal|name=Federal Democratic Republic of Nepal}}\n|20 September 2015\n|{{ayd|2015|09|20}}\n|[[Multi-party system|Multi-party]] [[parliamentary republic]]\n|Section 1, Article 4: \"Nepal is an independent, indivisible, sovereign, secular, inclusive democratic, socialism-oriented federal democratic republican state\".<ref>{{cite constitution|article=4|section=1|country=the Federal Democratic Republic of Nepal|language=|ratified=20 September 2015|url=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Nicaragua|name=Republic of Nicaragua}}\n|1 January 1987\n|{{ayd|1987|1|1}}\n|[[Dominant-party system|Dominant-party]] [[presidential republic]]\n|Section 1, Article 5: \"Liberty, justice, respect for the dignity of the human person, political and social pluralism, the recognition of the distinct identity of the indigenous peoples and those of African descent within the framework of a unitary and indivisible state, the recognition of different forms of property, free international cooperation and respect for the free self-determination of peoples, Christian values, socialist ideals, and practices based on solidarity, and the values and ideals of the Nicaraguan culture and identity, are the principles of the Nicaraguan nation. [...] The socialist ideals promote the common good over individual egoism, seeking to create an ever more inclusive, just and fair society, promoting an economic democracy which redistributes national wealth and eliminates exploitation among human beings\".<ref>{{cite constitution|article=5|section=1|country=the Republic of Nicaragua|language=|ratified=1 January 1987|url=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Portugal|name=Portuguese Republic}}\n|2 April 1976\n|{{ayd|1976|4|2}}\n|[[Multi-party system|Multi-party]] [[semi-presidential republic]]\n|Preamble: \"The Constituent Assembly affirms the Portuguese people's decision to [...] open up a path towards a socialist society\".<ref>{{cite constitution|article=Preamble|section=Preamble|country=the Portuguese Republic|language=|ratified=25 April 1976|url=http://www.en.parlamento.pt/Legislation/CRP/Constitution7th.pdf|accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Sri Lanka|name=Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka}}\n|7 September 1978\n|{{ayd|1978|9|7}}\n|[[Multi-party system|Multi-party]] [[semi-presidential republic]]\n|Preamble: \"[...] to constitute Sri Lanka into a democratic socialist republic whilst ratifying the immutable republican principles of representative democracy, and assuring to all peoples freedom, equality, justice, fundamental human rights and the independence of the judiciary\".<ref>{{cite constitution|article=Preamble|section=Preamble|country=the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka|language=|ratified=7 September 1978|url=http://www.priu.gov.lk/Cons/1978Constitution/Preamble.html|accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Tanzania|name=United Republic of Tanzania}}\n|26 April 1964\n|{{ayd|1964|4|26}}\n|[[Dominant-party system|Dominant-party]] [[semi-presidential republic]]\n|Section 1, Article 3: \"The United Republic is a democratic, secular and socialist state which adheres to multi-party democracy\".<ref>{{cite constitution|article=3|section=1|country=the United Republic of Tanzania|language=|ratified=25 April 1978|url=http://www.judiciary.go.tz/downloads/constitution.pdf|accessdate=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150421001106/http://www.judiciary.go.tz/downloads/constitution.pdf|archivedate=21 April 2015|df=}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==== Current socialist states with limited recognition ====\nThese are territories that have claimed independence or autonomy and have declared themselves socialist under some interpretation of the term. While these territories have created stable institutions of governance that have existed for a considerable period of time, they are not widely recognized as states by the international community and officially belong to other sovereign states under international law.\n* {{flagicon image|Flag_of_Christiania.svg}} [[Freetown Christiania]] (1971\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XuEHAUk18h4|title=Christiania: Copenhagen's Threatened Socialist Community|publisher=Journeyman Pictures|date=17 February 2015|accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the Wa Self-Administered Division.png}} [[Wa State]] (April 1989\u2013present)<ref>{{cite news|title=Wa State: Shanzhai Version Of China Discovered in Myanmar|url=http://www.chinasmack.com/2012/videos/shanzhai-version-china-discovered-myanmar.html|accessdate=20 January 2016|website=chinaSMACK|date=31 January 2012}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag_of_the_EZLN.svg}} [[Rebel Zapatista Autonomous Municipalities]] (December 1994\u2013present)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://links.org.au/mexico-zapatistas-ezln-oventic|title=Two decades on: A glimpse inside the Zapatista's capital, Oventic|last=Mallett-Outtrim|first=Ryan|work=Links International Journal of Socialist Renewal|date=13 August 2016|accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag_of_Rojava.svg}} [[Rojava|Autonomous Administration of North and East Syria]] (November 2013\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://new-compass.net/articles/revolutionary-education-rojava|title=Revolutionary Education in Rojava|publisher=New Compass|date=17 February 2015|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Multi-party states with governing communist or socialist parties ==\nThere are multi-party states with [[Communist party|communist]] or [[socialist parties]] leading the government, sometimes together. Such states are not considered to be communist or socialist states because the countries themselves allow for multiple parties and do not provide a constitutional role for their communist parties or socialism. This list does not include socialist parties following [[social democracy]] which governed most of the [[Western world]] as part of the mainstream [[centre-left]]. It mainly includes [[democratic socialist]] parties positioned to their left. \n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Country\n!scope=\"col\"|Party\n!scope=\"col\"|Electoral coalition\n!scope=\"col\"|Election\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"|Lower house\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"|Upper house\n!scope=\"col\"|Official ideology\n|-\n|{{flag|Algeria}}{{refn|Constitutionally a socialist state.|group=\"nb\"}}\n|[[National Liberation Front (Algeria)|National Liberation Front]]\n|\u2014 || [[2017 Algerian legislative election|2017]] || {{composition bar|164|462|hex=#DC241f}} || \u2014 || [[Arab socialism]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Angola}}{{refn|Formerly a Marxist\u2013Leninist state.|group=\"nb\"}}\n|[[MPLA|People's Movement for the Liberation of Angola]]\n|\u2014 || [[2017 Angolan legislative election|2017]] || {{composition bar|150|220|hex=#DC241f}} || \u2014 || [[Democratic socialism]]<br>[[Vanguardism]]<ref>[http://www.mpla.ao/imagem/1%20-%20PROGRAMA%20E%20ESTATUTOS.pdf \"MPLA Programa Dezembro 2009\"] (in Spanish). 10 December 2009. Retrieved 29 December 2019.</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|{{flag|Bangladesh}}{{refn|Constitutionally a socialist state.|group=\"nb\"}}\n|[[Bangladesh Awami League]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Grand Alliance (Bangladesh)|Grand Alliance]] || rowspan=\"3\"|[[2014 Bangladeshi general election|2014]] || rowspan=\"3\"|{{composition bar|293|350|hex=#DC241f}} || rowspan=\"3\"| \u2014 || [[Socialism]]\n|-\n|[[Workers Party of Bangladesh]]\n|[[Marxism\u2013Leninism]]\n|-\n|[[Jatiya Samajtantrik Dal]]\n|