ag of the Chinese Communist Party (Pre-1996).svg}} [[Guangzhou Uprising|Guangzhou Commune (Guangzhou Soviet)]] (11 December 1927 \u2013 13 December 1927)\n* {{flagicon image|\u4e2d\u570b\u5de5\u8fb2\u7d05\u8ecd\u8ecd\u65d7.svg}} [[Communist-controlled China (1927\u20131949)|Soviet Zone]] (1927\u20131937)\n* {{flagicon image|BlackFlag.svg}} [[Korean People's Association in Manchuria]] (1929\u20131931)\n* {{flagicon image|Communist Party of Vietnam flag.svg}} [[Ngh\u1ec7-T\u0129nh Soviets|Ngh\u1ec7-T\u0129nh Soviet]] (1930\u20131931)\n* {{flagicon image|Chinese_soviet_flag.svg}} [[Jiangxi\u2013Fujian Soviet]] (1931\u20131934)\n* {{flag|Chinese Soviet Republic}} (7 November 1931 \u2013 22 September 1937)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Chile.svg}} [[Socialist Republic of Chile]] (4 June 1932 \u2013 2 October 1932)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Fujian People's Government.svg}} [[Fujian People's Government|People's Revolutionary Government of the Republic of China]] (22 November 1933 \u2013 13 January 1934)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Xinjiang-Shicai 2.svg}} [[Xinjiang clique|Xinjiang Clique]] (1934\u20131941)\n* {{flagicon image|Socialist red flag.svg}} [[Asturian miners' strike of 1934|Asturian Socialist Republic]] (October 1934)\n* [[Regional Defence Council of Aragon]] (1936\u20131937)\n* {{flagicon image|CNT_FAI_flag.png}} [[Anarchist Aragon]] (1936\u20131939)\n* {{flagicon image|CNT_FAI_flag.png}} [[Revolutionary Catalonia]] (1936\u20131939)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the Republic of China.svg}} [[Shaan-Gan-Ning Border Region]] (1937\u20131946)\n* {{flagicon|Finland}} [[Finnish Democratic Republic]] (December 1939 \u2013 March 1940)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Greece (1822-1978).svg}} [[Political Committee of National Liberation]] (10 March 1944 \u2013 9 October 1944)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Inner-Mongolian Autonomous Government.svg}} [[Inner Mongolian People's Republic]] (9 September 1945 \u2013 6 November 1945)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the People%27s Committee of Korea.svg}} [[People's Republic of Korea]] (1945\u20131946)\n* {{flagicon image|Second War Flag of Chinese Soviet Republic.svg}} [[Communist-controlled China (1927\u20131949)|Liberated Zone]] (1946\u20131949)\n* {{flagicon image|Azerbaijan people's government flag.svg}} [[Azerbaijan People's Government]] (November 1945 \u2013 December 1946)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the Republic of Mahabad.svg}} [[Republic of Mahabad]] (22 January 1946 \u2013 15 December 1946)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the Provisional People's Committee for North Korea.svg}} [[Provisional People's Committee for North Korea]] (1946\u20131947)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the Provisional People's Committee for North Korea.svg}} [[People's Committee of North Korea]] (1947\u20131948)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Greece (1822-1978).svg}} [[Provisional Democratic Government|Provisional Democratic Government of North Greece]] (1947\u20131949)\n* {{flagicon image|Single_Color_Flag_-_BF0000.svg}} [[Marquetalia Republic]] (1948\u20131958)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the Second East Turkestan Republic.svg}} [[Second East Turkestan Republic]] (12 November 1949 \u2013 20 December 1949)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Zanzibar (January-April 1964).svg}} [[People's Republic of Zanzibar|People's Republic of Zanzibar and Pemba]] (12 January 1964 \u2013 26 April 1964)\n* {{flagicon image|FNL Flag.svg}} [[Provisional Revolutionary Government of the Republic of South Vietnam]] (8 June 1969 \u2013 2 June 1976)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of People's Provisional Government of Vanuat (1977-1978).svg}} [[Vanua'aku Pati|People's Provisional Government of Vanuatu]] (1977\u20131978)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Grenada.svg}} [[People's Revolutionary Government (Grenada)|People's Revolutionary Government of Grenada]] (1979\u20131983)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Guinea.svg}} [[History of Guinea#S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9's rule (1958\u20131984)|People's Revolutionary Republic of Guinea]] (1979\u20131984)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of The Gambia.svg}} [[Kukoi Sanyang|National Revolutionary Council of Gambia]] (30 July 1981 \u2013 5 August 1981)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag_of_Democratic_Kampuchea.svg}} [[Coalition Government of Democratic Kampuchea]] (22 June 1982 \u2013 15 March 1992)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Burkina Faso.svg}} [[Committees for the Defense of the Revolution (Burkina Faso)|National Council for the Revolution]] (1984\u20131987)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of South Yemen.svg}} [[Democratic Republic of Yemen]] (21 May 1994 \u2013 7 July 1994)\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Democratic_Kampuchea.svg}} [[Provisional Government of National Union and National Salvation of Cambodia]] (11 July 1994 \u2013 22 June 1998)\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Communism|Socialism}}\n* [[People's republic]]\n* [[Socialism in one country]]\n* [[List of former communist states and socialist states]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=nb|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{current Communist rulers}}\n{{current Socialist rulers}}\n[[Category:Lists of countries|Socialist]]\n[[Category:Socialism|States]]\n[[Category:Socialism-related lists|States]]\n[[Category:Socialist states|*]]\n", "name_user": "Davide King", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEphemeral socialist states:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_socialist_states"}
{"title_page": "Independence of Brazil", "text_new": "{{short description|Independence movement}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox historical event\n  |partof = the [[War of Independence of Brazil]]\n  |Event_Name     =Independence of Brazil, y son bien malos basura \n  |Image_Name     = Independ\u00eancia ou Morte (1888).jpg\n  |alt            = Painting depicting a group of uniformed men on horseback riding towards a smaller group of mounted men who have halted at the top of a small hill with the uniformed man at the front of the smaller group raising a sword high into the air \"[[Cry of Ipiranga|Independence or Death!]]\"\n  |Image_Caption  = Declaration of Brazil's independence by [[Pedro I of Brazil|Prince Pedro]], regent on 7 September 1822. His Guard of Honor greets him in support while some discard blue and white armbands that represented loyalty to [[Portugal]]. Painting [[Independence or Death (painting)|''Independence or Death'']] by [[Pedro Am\u00e9rico]].\n  |Participants   = [[Pedro I of Brazil|Prince Pedro]]<br>[[Maria Leopoldina of Austria|Archduchess Leopoldina]]<br>[[Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio de Andrada]]\n  |Location       = [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Brazil]]\n  |Date           = 7 September 1822\n  |Result         = Independence of the [[Kingdom of Brazil]] from the [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves]] and subsequent formation of the [[Empire of Brazil]] under Emperor Dom [[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro I]] (1798-1834, reigned 1822-1834)\n}}\nThe '''Independence of Brazil''' comprised a series of political and military events that occurred in 1821\u20131824, most of which involved disputes between [[Brazil]] and [[Portugal]] regarding the call for independence presented by the [[Brazilian Empire]].\n\nIt is celebrated on [[Independence Day (Brazil)|7 September]], the anniversary of the date in 1822 that prince regent [[Pedro I of Brazil|Dom Pedro]] declared Brazil's independence from the former [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and Algarves]]. Formal recognition came with a treaty three years later, signed by both the new [[Empire of Brazil]] and the [[Kingdom of Portugal]] in late 1825.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Oscar Pereira da Silva - Desembarque de Pedro \u00c1lvares Cabral em Porto Seguro em 1500.jpg|thumb|left|240px|Landing of [[Pedro \u00c1lvares Cabral]] in Brazil, South America, 1500.]]\n\nThe land now called Brazil was claimed by the [[Portugal|Kingdom of Portugal]] in April 1500, on the arrival of the Portuguese naval fleet commanded by [[Pedro \u00c1lvares Cabral]]. The Portuguese encountered Indigenous nations divided into several tribes, most of whom shared the same [[Tupi\u2013Guarani languages]] family, and shared and disputed the territory. But the Portuguese, like the Spanish in their North American territories, had brought diseases with them against which many Indians were helpless due to lack of immunity. Measles, smallpox, tuberculosis, and influenza killed tens of thousands{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThough the first settlement was founded in 1532, colonization was effectively started in 1534 when [[John III of Portugal|King John III]] divided the territory into fifteen hereditary captaincies. This arrangement proved problematic, however, and in 1549 the king assigned a Governor-General to administer the entire colony. The Portuguese assimilated some of the native tribes while others slowly disappeared in long wars or by [[Europe]]an diseases to which they had no immunity.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nBy the mid-16th century, [[sugar]] had become Brazil's most important export due to the increasing international demand for sugar. To profit from the situation, by 1700 over 963,000 African slaves had been brought across the [[Atlantic Ocean]] to work in the plantations of Brazil. More Africans were brought to Brazil up until that date than to all the other places in [[Americas|The Americas]] ([[Western Hemisphere]]) combined.<ref>See the tables [http://www.slavevoyages.org/tast/assessment/estimates.faces '''here'''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131027021745/http://www.slavevoyages.org/tast/assessment/estimates.faces |date=2013-10-27 }}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width     = 210\n | image1    = Departure of H.R.H. the Prince Regent of Portugal for the Brazils (Campaigns of the British Army in Portugal, London, 1812) - Henry L'Ev\u00eaque, F. Bartollozzi.png\n | caption1  = Departure of the [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portuguese]] royal family of the  [[House of Braganza]] to exile in Brazil on 29 November 1807, under pressure from [[First French Empire|French]] Emperor [[Napoleon Bonaparte|Napoleon I]].\n | image2    = Aclama\u00e7\u00e3o do rei Dom Jo\u00e3o VI no Rio de Janeiro.jpg\n | caption2  = Acclamation ceremony of [[John VI of Portugal|King John VI]] of the new [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], temporary capital, [[Kingdom of Brazil|Brazil]], 6 February 1818.\n}}\nThrough wars against the [[Kingdom of France|French]], the Portuguese slowly expanded their territory to the southeast, taking [[Rio de Janeiro]] in 1567, and to the northwest, taking S\u00e3o Lu\u00eds in 1615. They sent military expeditions to the northwest of the [[South America]]n continent to the [[Amazon River]] basin rainforest and conquered competing [[Kingdom of England|English]] and [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] strongholds, founding villages and forts from 1669. In 1680 they reached the far southeast and founded [[Sacramento (Uruguay)|Sacramento]] on the bank of the [[Rio de la Plata]], in the ''[[Banda Oriental]]'' region (present-day [[Uruguay]]).{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nAt the end of the 17th century, sugar exports started to decline, but beginning in the 1690s, the discovery of gold by explorers in the region that would later be called [[Minas Gerais]] (General Mines) in current [[Mato Grosso]], [[Goi\u00e1s]] and the Brazilian state of [[Minas Gerais]] saved the colony from imminent collapse. From all over Brazil, as well as from Portugal, thousands of immigrants came to the mines in an early \"gold rush\".{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe [[Kingdom of Spain|Spanish]] tried to prevent Portuguese expansion northwest, west, southwest and southeast into the territory that belonged to them according to the 1494 [[Treaty of Tordesillas]] division of the [[New World]] of [[Americas|The Americas]] by the [[Bishop of Rome|Bishop and Pope of Rome]], [[Pope Alexander VI]] (1431-1503, reigned 1492-1503) and succeeded in conquering the ''Banda Oriental'' region in 1777. However, this was in vain as the [[First Treaty of San Ildefonso|Treaty of San Ildefonso]], signed in the same year, confirmed Portuguese sovereignty over all lands proceeding from its territorial expansion, thus creating most of the current Brazilian southeastern border.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nDuring the [[Invasion of Portugal (1807)|French invasion of Portugal]], by Emperor [[Napoleon Bonaparte|Napoleon I]] in 1807, the Portuguese royal family [[House of Braganza]] fled across the [[Atlantic Ocean]] with the help of the British [[Royal Navy]] to Brazil, establishing [[Rio de Janeiro]] as the de facto capital of Portugal and Brazil and the [[Portuguese Empire]] during the ensuing worldwide [[Napoleonic Wars]] (1803-1815).  This had the side effect of soon creating within Brazil, many of the institutions required to exist as an independent state; most importantly, it freed Brazil to trade with other nations at will.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nAfter Napoleon's Imperial French army was finally defeated at [[Battle of Waterloo|Waterloo]] in June 1815, in order to maintain the capital in Brazil and allay Brazilian fears of being returned to colonial status, [[King John VI of Portugal]] raised the [[de jure]] status of Brazil to an equal, integral part of a new status in a [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil, and the Algarves]], rather than a mere colony, a status which it enjoyed for the next seven years, sending his son, Dom [[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro]] as prince regent.\n\n==Path to independence==\n===Portuguese ''Cortes''===\n[[File:Portuguese Cortes 1822.jpg|left|thumb|200px|The Portuguese ''Cortes'']]\nIn 1820 the [[Liberal Revolution of 1820|Constitutionalist Revolution]] erupted in [[Portugal]]. The movement initiated by the liberal constitutionalists resulted in the meeting of the ''[[Constituent Cortes of 1820|Cortes]]'' (or [[Constituent Assembly]]), that would have to create the kingdom's first [[constitution]].<ref>Lustosa, p.97</ref><ref>Armitage. p.36</ref> The ''Cortes'' at the same time demanded the return of King [[Don (honorific)|Dom]] [[John VI of Portugal|John VI]], who had been living in [[Brazil]] since 1808, who elevated Brazil to a kingdom as part of the [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves]] in 1815 and who nominated his son and heir prince Dom [[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro]] as [[regent]], to govern Brazil in his place on 7 March 1821.<ref>Lustosa, p.106</ref><ref>Armitage. p. 38</ref> The king left for Europe on 26 April, while Dom Pedro remained in Brazil governing it with the aid of the ministers of the Kingdom (Interior) and Foreign Affairs, [[Ministry of Defence (Brazil)|of War, of Navy]] and [[Ministry of Finance (Brazil)|of Finance]].<ref>Lustosa, pp. 109\u201310</ref><ref>Armitage. p. 41</ref>\n\nThe Portuguese military officers headquartered in Brazil were completely sympathetic to the Constitutionalist movement in Portugal.<ref>Lustosa, p. 112</ref> The main leader of the Portuguese officers, General [[Jorge de Avilez Zuzarte de Sousa Tavares]] forced the prince to dismiss and banish from the country the ministers of Kingdom and Finance. Both were loyal allies of Pedro, who had become a pawn in the hands of the military.<ref>Lustosa, pp. 113\u201314</ref> The humiliation suffered by the prince, who swore he would never yield to the pressure of the military again, would have a decisive influence on his abdication ten years later.<ref>Lustosa, p. 114</ref> Meanwhile, on 30 September 1821, the ''Cortes'' approved a decree that subordinated the governments of the [[Brazilian provinces]] directly to Portugal. Prince Pedro became for all purposes only the governor of the [[Rio de Janeiro Province]].<ref name=\"Lustosa, p.117\">Lustosa, p. 117</ref><ref>Armitage. pp. 43\u201344</ref> Other decrees that came after ordered his return to Europe and also extinguished the judicial courts created by Jo\u00e3o VI in 1808.<ref name=\"Lustosa, p.119\">Lustosa, p.119</ref><ref>Armitage. pp. 48\u201351</ref>\n\nDissatisfaction over the ''Cortes'' measures among most residents in Brazil (both Brazilian-born and Portuguese-born) rose to a point that it soon became publicly known.<ref name=\"Lustosa, p.117\"/> Two groups that opposed the ''Cortes''' actions to gradually undermine the Brazilian sovereignty appeared: Liberals led by [[Joaquim Gon\u00e7alves Ledo]] (which had the support of the [[Freemason]]s) and the Bonifacians led by [[Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio de Andrada e Silva|Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio de Andrada]]. Both factions had nothing in common in their goals for Brazil, with the sole exception of their desire to keep the country united with Portugal as a sovereign monarchy.<ref>Di\u00e9gues, p. 70</ref>\n\n===Avilez rebellion===\n[[File:Pedro I of Brazil and Avilez.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Prince Pedro (right) orders Portuguese officer [[Jorge de Avilez Zuzarte de Sousa Tavares|Jorge de Avilez]] (left) to return to Portugal after his failed rebellion, 8 February 1822. [[Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio de Andrada e Silva|Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio]] (in civilian clothes) can be seen next to the prince.]]\nThe Portuguese deputies of the ''Cortes'' showed no respect towards the prince and openly mocked him.<ref>Lustosa, p.120</ref> And so the loyalty that Pedro had shown towards the ''Cortes'' gradually shifted to the Brazilian cause.<ref name=\"Lustosa, p.119\"/> His wife, princess [[Maria Leopoldina of Austria|Leopoldina of Habsburg]], favoured the Brazilian side and encouraged him to remain in the country<ref>Lustosa, pp. 121\u201322</ref> while the Liberals and Bonifacians made open representations. Pedro's reply came on 9 January 1822, who, according to newspapers, spoke: \"As it is for the good of all and for the nation's general happiness, I am ready: Tell the people that I will stay\".<ref>Lustosa, pp. 123-24</ref>\n\nAfter Pedro's decision to defy the ''Cortes'', around 2,000 men led by Jorge Avilez rioted before concentrating on mount Castelo, which was soon surrounded by 10,000 armed Brazilians, led by the [[Rio de Janeiro State Military Police|Royal Police Guard]].<ref>Lustosa, pp. 132\u201334</ref> Dom Pedro then \"dismissed\" the Portuguese commanding general and ordered him to remove his soldiers across the bay to [[Niter\u00f3i]], where they would await transport to Portugal.<ref>Lustosa, p. 135</ref>\n\nJose Bonif\u00e1cio was nominated minister of Kingdom and Foreign Affairs on 18 January 1822.<ref>Lustosa, p. 138</ref> Bonif\u00e1cio soon established a fatherlike relationship with Pedro, who began to consider the experienced [[politician|statesman]] his greatest ally.<ref>Lustosa, p. 139</ref> Gon\u00e7alves Ledo and the liberals tried to minimize the close relationship between Bonif\u00e1cio and Pedro offering to the prince the title of Perpetual Defender of Brazil.<ref name=\"Lustosa, p.143\">Lustosa, p. 143</ref><ref name=\"Armitage. p.61\">Armitage. p. 61</ref> For the liberals, the meeting of a Constituent Assembly for Brazil was necessary, while the Bonifacians preferred that Pedro grant the constitution himself to avoid the possibility of similar anarchy to the one that occurred during the first years of the [[French Revolution]].<ref name=\"Lustosa, p.143\"/>\n\nThe prince acquiesced to the liberals\u2019 desires and signed a decree on 3 June 1822 calling for the election of the deputies that would gather in the [[Constituent assembly|Constituent and Legislative General Assembly]] in Brazil.<ref name=\"Armitage. p.61\"/><ref>Lustosa, p. 145</ref>\n\n===From united kingdom to independent empire===\n{{more citations needed|section|date=June 2017}}\n[[File:Independencia brasil 001.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Prince Pedro is surrounded by a cheering crowd in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] after giving the news of the Brazilian independence on 7 September 1822.]]\nPedro departed to [[S\u00e3o Paulo Province]] to secure the province's loyalty to the Brazilian cause. He reached its [[S\u00e3o Paulo|capital]] on 25 August and remained there until 5 September. While on his way back to Rio de Janeiro on 7 September he received mail from Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio and his wife, Leopoldina.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} The letter told him that the ''Cortes'' had annulled all acts from the Bonif\u00e1cio cabinet, removed Pedro's remaining powers and ordered him to return to Portugal.  It was clear that independence was the only option left. Pedro turned to his companions that included his [[Presidential Guard Battalion (Brazil)|Guard of Honor]] and spoke: \"Friends, the Portuguese ''Cortes'' want to enslave and pursue us. From today on our relations are broken. No ties can unite us anymore\" and continued after he pulled out his blue-white armband that symbolized Portugal: \"Armbands off, soldiers. Hail to the independence, to freedom and to the separation of Brazil from Portugal!\" He unsheathed his sword affirming that \"For my blood, my honor, my God, I swear to give Brazil freedom,\" and later cried out: \"Brazilians, Independence or death!\". This event is remembered as \"[[Cry of Ipiranga]]\".<ref>Lustosa, pp. 150\u201353</ref>\n\nReturning to the city of [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] on the night of 7 September 1822, [[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro]] and his companions announced the news of Brazilian independence from Portugal. The Prince was received with great popular celebration and was called not only \"King of Brazil\", but also \"Emperor of Brazil\".<ref name=\"Vianna, p.408\">Vianna, p. 408</ref><ref>Lima (1997), p. 398</ref>\n\n[[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro]] returned to [[Rio de Janeiro]] on 14 September and in the following days the liberals had spread pamphlets (written by [[Joaquim Gon\u00e7alves Ledo]]) that suggested the idea that the Prince should be acclaimed [[Constitutional monarchy|Constitutional Emperor]].<ref name=\"Vianna, p.408\"/> On 17 September the President of the [[Municipal council|Municipal Chamber]] of Rio de Janeiro, Jos\u0117 Clemente Pereira, sent to the other Chambers of the country the news that the [[Acclamation]] would occur in the anniversary of Pedro on 12 October.<ref>Lustosa, p. 153</ref>\n[[File:Coroa\u00e7ao pedro I 001.jpg|right|thumb|240px|Coronation of Emperor Pedro I on December 1, 1822.]]\nThe official separation would only occur on 22 September 1822 in a letter written by Pedro to [[John VI of Portugal|Jo\u00e3o VI]]. In it, Pedro still calls himself Prince Regent and his father is considered the King of the independent Brazil.<ref>Lima (1997), p. 379</ref><ref>Vianna, p. 413</ref> On 12 October 1822, in the Field of Santana (later known as Field of the Acclamation) Prince Pedro was acclaimed Dom Pedro I, Constitutional Emperor and Perpetual Defender of Brazil. It was at the same time the beginning of Pedro's reign and also of the [[Empire of Brazil]].<ref>Vianna, pp. 417\u201318</ref> However, the Emperor made it clear that although he accepted the emperorship, if Jo\u00e3o VI returned to Brazil he would step down from the throne in favor of his father.<ref>Lima (1997), p. 404</ref>\n\nThe reason for the imperial title was that the title of king would symbolically mean a continuation of the Portuguese dynastic tradition and perhaps of the feared absolutism, while the title of emperor derived from popular acclamation as in [[Ancient Rome]] or at least reigning through popular sanction as in the case of Napoleon.<ref>Lima (1997), p.339</ref><ref>Barman (1999), p. 4; \"Some weeks later he was acclaimed emperor as Pedro I of Brazil. In the terminology of the period, the word 'empire' signifying a monarchy of unusually large size and resources (as in the case of Russia), and this designation avoided D. Pedro's usurping the title of 'king' from his father, Jo\u00e3o VI.\"</ref> On 1 December 1822, Pedro I was crowned and consecrated.<ref>Vianna, p. 418</ref>\n\n==War of Independence==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2017}}\n\n{{main|War of Independence of Brazil}}\n[[File:Entrada do Ex\u00e9rcito Libertador 1930.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Brazilian Army]] entering [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]] after the surrender of the Portuguese forces in 1823.]]\n\nBut in spite of these fine words, the new flag and the Acclamation of Pedro as Constitutional Emperor, the authority of the new regime only extended to Rio de Janeiro, S\u00e3o Paulo and the adjacent provinces. The rest of Brazil remained firmly under the control of Portuguese juntas and garrisons.  It would take a war to put the whole of Brazil under Pedro's control.  The fighting began with skirmishes between rival militias in 1822 and lasted until January 1824, when the last Portuguese garrisons and naval units surrendered or left the country.\n\nMeanwhile, the Imperial government had to create a regular [[Brazilian Army|Army]] and [[Brazilian Navy|Navy]].  Forced enlistment was widespread, extending to foreign immigrants, and Brazil made use of slaves in militias, as well as freeing slaves to enlist them in army and navy. The campaigns on land and sea covered the vast territories of [[Bahia]], [[Montevideo and Cisplatina]], Gr\u00e3o-Par\u00e1. [[Maranh\u00e3o]], [[Pernambuco]], [[Cear\u00e1]] and [[Piau\u00ed]].\n\nBy 1822, Brazilian forces were firmly in control of [[Rio de Janeiro]] and the central area of Brazil.  Loyal militias began insurrections in the aforementioned territories, but strong, and regularly reinforced Portuguese garrisons in the port cities of  [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]], [[Montevideo]], [[S\u00e3o Lu\u00eds, Maranh\u00e3o|S\u00e3o Lu\u00eds]] and [[Bel\u00e9m]] continued to dominate the adjacent areas and to pose the threat of a reconquest that the irregular Brazilian militias and [[guerrilla]] forces, which were loosely besieging them by land supported by newly created units of the Brazilian army, would be unable to prevent.\n\nFor the Brazilians, the answer to this stalemate was to seize control of the sea.  Eleven former Portuguese warships, great and small, had fallen into Brazilian hands in Rio de Janeiro and these formed the basis of a new navy. The problem was manpower: the crews of these ships were largely Portuguese who were openly mutinous, and although many Portuguese naval officers had declared allegiance to Brazil their loyalty could not be relied on.  The Brazilian Government solved the problem by recruiting 50 officers and 500 seamen in secret in London and Liverpool, many of them veterans of the Napoleonic Wars, and appointed [[Thomas Cochrane, 10th Earl of Dundonald|Thomas Cochrane]] as commander-in-chief.<ref>Brian Vale 'Independence or Death: British Sailors and Brazilian Independence' I B Tauris, 1995</ref>\nOn 1 April 1823, a Brazilian squadron of 6 ships sailed for Bahia.  After an initial disappointing engagement with a superior Portuguese fleet, Cochrane blockaded Salvador.  Deprived now of supplies and reinforcements by sea and besieged by the Brazilian army on land, on 2 July the Portuguese forces abandoned Bahia in a convoy of 90 ships.  Leaving the frigate \u2018Niteroi\u2019 under Captain John Taylor to harry them to the coasts of Europe, Cochrane then sailed north to S\u00e3o Lu\u00eds (Maranh\u00e3o).  There he tricked the Portuguese garrison into evacuating Maranh\u00e3o by pretending that a huge Brazilian fleet and army were over the  horizon.  He then sent Captain John Pascoe Grenfell to play the same trick on the Portuguese in Bel\u00e9m do Par\u00e1 at the mouth of the Amazon.<ref>Brian Vale 'The Audacious Admiral Cochrane; The True Life of a Naval Legend',  Conway, 2004</ref>  By November 1823, the whole of the north of Brazil was under Brazilian control, and the following month, the demoralized Portuguese also evacuated Montevideo and the Cisplatine Province.  By 1824, Brazil was free of all enemy troops and was \u2018de facto\u2019 independent.<ref>Vale</ref>\n\nThere are still today no reliable [[statistics]]<ref>{{in lang|pt}} [[:pt:Laurentino Gomes|Laurentino Gomes]] [[1822 (book)|''1822'']] Nova Fronteira, Brasil 2010 {{ISBN|85-209-2409-3}} Chapter 10, p. 163</ref> related to the numbers of, for example, the total of the war casualties. However based upon historical registration and contemporary reports of some battles of this war as well as upon the admitted numbers in similar fights that happened in these times around the globe, and considering how long the Brazilian independence war lasted (22 months), estimates of all killed in action on both sides are placed from around 5,700 to 6,200.\n\n===In Pernambuco===\n* [[Siege of Recife]]\n\n===In Piau\u00ed and Maranh\u00e3o===\n* [[Battle of Jenipapo]]\n* [[Siege of Caxias]]\n\n===In Gr\u00e3o-Par\u00e1===\n* [[Siege of Bel\u00e9m]]\n\n===In Bahia===\n* [[Battle of Piraj\u00e1]]\n* [[Battle of Itaparica]]\n* [[Battle of 4 May]]\n* [[Siege of Salvador]]\n\n===In Cisplatina===\n* [[Siege of Montevideo (1823)]]\n\n==Peace treaty and aftermath==\nThe last Portuguese soldiers left Brazil in 1824.  A peace treaty recognizing Brazil's independence was drafted in summer 1825, and signed by Brazil and Portugal that autumn.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Brazil}}\n* [[Empire of Brazil]]\n* [[Colonial Brazil]]\n* [[Cry of Ipiranga]]\n* [[History of Brazil]]\n* [[Treaty of Rio de Janeiro (1825)]]\n* [[Independence Day (Brazil)]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* Gomes, Laurentino, ''[[1822 (book)|1822]]''<!-- ISSN/ISBN, publisher, year of publication needed -->\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=25em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* Armitage, John. ''Hist\u00f3ria do Brasil''. Belo Horizonte: Itatiaia, 1981. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Barman, Roderick J. ''Citizen Emperor: Pedro II and the Making of Brazil, 1825\u20131891.'' Stanford: Stanford University Press, 1999. {{in lang|en}}\n* Di\u00e9gues, Fernando. ''A revolu\u00e7\u00e3o bras\u00edlica''. Rio de Janeiro: Objetiva, 2004. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Dolhnikoff, Miriam. ''Pacto imperial: origens do federalismo no Brasil do s\u00e9culo XIX''. S\u00e3o Paulo: Globo, 2005. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Gomes, Laurentino. [[1822 (book)|''1822'']]. Nova Fronteira, 2010. {{ISBN|85-209-2409-3}} {{in lang|pt}}\n* Holanda, S\u00e9rgio Buarque de. ''O Brasil Mon\u00e1rquico: o processo de emancipa\u00e7\u00e3o''. 4. ed. S\u00e3o Paulo: Difus\u00e3o Europ\u00e9ia do Livro, 1976. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Lima, Manuel de Oliveira. ''O movimento da independ\u00eancia''. 6. ed. Rio de Janeiro: Topbooks, 1997. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Lustosa, Isabel. ''D. Pedro I''. S\u00e3o Paulo: Companhia das Letras, 2007. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Vainfas, Ronaldo. ''Dicion\u00e1rio do Brasil Imperial''. Rio de Janeiro: Objetiva, 2002. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Vianna, H\u00e9lio. ''Hist\u00f3ria do Brasil: per\u00edodo colonial, monarquia e rep\u00fablica''. 15. ed. S\u00e3o Paulo: Melhoramentos, 1994. {{in lang|pt}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n{{Brazil topics}}\n\n[[Category:1820s conflicts]]\n[[Category:Empire of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Military history of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Latin American wars of independence]]\n[[Category:1822 in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Separatism in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Separatism in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Brazil]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Portugal]]\n[[Category:Wars of independence]]\n[[Category:Brazil\u2013Portugal relations]]\n[[Category:1822 in international relations]]\n[[Category:Pedro I of Brazil]]\n\n[[it:Impero del Brasile#Indipendenza brasiliana]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Independence movement}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox historical event\n  |partof = the [[War of Independence of Brazil]]\n  |Event_Name     =Independence of Brazil\n  |Image_Name     = Independ\u00eancia ou Morte (1888).jpg\n  |alt            = Painting depicting a group of uniformed men on horseback riding towards a smaller group of mounted men who have halted at the top of a small hill with the uniformed man at the front of the smaller group raising a sword high into the air \"[[Cry of Ipiranga|Independence or Death!]]\"\n  |Image_Caption  = Declaration of Brazil's independence by [[Pedro I of Brazil|Prince Pedro]], regent on 7 September 1822. His Guard of Honor greets him in support while some discard blue and white armbands that represented loyalty to [[Portugal]]. Painting [[Independence or Death (painting)|''Independence or Death'']] by [[Pedro Am\u00e9rico]].\n  |Participants   = [[Pedro I of Brazil|Prince Pedro]]<br>[[Maria Leopoldina of Austria|Archduchess Leopoldina]]<br>[[Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio de Andrada]]\n  |Location       = [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Brazil]]\n  |Date           = 7 September 1822\n  |Result         = Independence of the [[Kingdom of Brazil]] from the [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves]] and subsequent formation of the [[Empire of Brazil]] under Emperor Dom [[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro I]] (1798-1834, reigned 1822-1834)\n}}\nThe '''Independence of Brazil''' comprised a series of political and military events that occurred in 1821\u20131824, most of which involved disputes between [[Brazil]] and [[Portugal]] regarding the call for independence presented by the [[Brazilian Empire]].\n\nIt is celebrated on [[Independence Day (Brazil)|7 September]], the anniversary of the date in 1822 that prince regent [[Pedro I of Brazil|Dom Pedro]] declared Brazil's independence from the former [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and Algarves]]. Formal recognition came with a treaty three years later, signed by both the new [[Empire of Brazil]] and the [[Kingdom of Portugal]] in late 1825.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Oscar Pereira da Silva - Desembarque de Pedro \u00c1lvares Cabral em Porto Seguro em 1500.jpg|thumb|left|240px|Landing of [[Pedro \u00c1lvares Cabral]] in Brazil, South America, 1500.]]\n\nThe land now called Brazil was claimed by the [[Portugal|Kingdom of Portugal]] in April 1500, on the arrival of the Portuguese naval fleet commanded by [[Pedro \u00c1lvares Cabral]]. The Portuguese encountered Indigenous nations divided into several tribes, most of whom shared the same [[Tupi\u2013Guarani languages]] family, and shared and disputed the territory. But the Portuguese, like the Spanish in their North American territories, had brought diseases with them against which many Indians were helpless due to lack of immunity. Measles, smallpox, tuberculosis, and influenza killed tens of thousands{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThough the first settlement was founded in 1532, colonization was effectively started in 1534 when [[John III of Portugal|King John III]] divided the territory into fifteen hereditary captaincies. This arrangement proved problematic, however, and in 1549 the king assigned a Governor-General to administer the entire colony. The Portuguese assimilated some of the native tribes while others slowly disappeared in long wars or by [[Europe]]an diseases to which they had no immunity.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nBy the mid-16th century, [[sugar]] had become Brazil's most important export due to the increasing international demand for sugar. To profit from the situation, by 1700 over 963,000 African slaves had been brought across the [[Atlantic Ocean]] to work in the plantations of Brazil. More Africans were brought to Brazil up until that date than to all the other places in [[Americas|The Americas]] ([[Western Hemisphere]]) combined.<ref>See the tables [http://www.slavevoyages.org/tast/assessment/estimates.faces '''here'''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131027021745/http://www.slavevoyages.org/tast/assessment/estimates.faces |date=2013-10-27 }}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width     = 210\n | image1    = Departure of H.R.H. the Prince Regent of Portugal for the Brazils (Campaigns of the British Army in Portugal, London, 1812) - Henry L'Ev\u00eaque, F. Bartollozzi.png\n | caption1  = Departure of the [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portuguese]] royal family of the  [[House of Braganza]] to exile in Brazil on 29 November 1807, under pressure from [[First French Empire|French]] Emperor [[Napoleon Bonaparte|Napoleon I]].\n | image2    = Aclama\u00e7\u00e3o do rei Dom Jo\u00e3o VI no Rio de Janeiro.jpg\n | caption2  = Acclamation ceremony of [[John VI of Portugal|King John VI]] of the new [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], temporary capital, [[Kingdom of Brazil|Brazil]], 6 February 1818.\n}}\nThrough wars against the [[Kingdom of France|French]], the Portuguese slowly expanded their territory to the southeast, taking [[Rio de Janeiro]] in 1567, and to the northwest, taking S\u00e3o Lu\u00eds in 1615. They sent military expeditions to the northwest of the [[South America]]n continent to the [[Amazon River]] basin rainforest and conquered competing [[Kingdom of England|English]] and [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] strongholds, founding villages and forts from 1669. In 1680 they reached the far southeast and founded [[Sacramento (Uruguay)|Sacramento]] on the bank of the [[Rio de la Plata]], in the ''[[Banda Oriental]]'' region (present-day [[Uruguay]]).{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nAt the end of the 17th century, sugar exports started to decline, but beginning in the 1690s, the discovery of gold by explorers in the region that would later be called [[Minas Gerais]] (General Mines) in current [[Mato Grosso]], [[Goi\u00e1s]] and the Brazilian state of [[Minas Gerais]] saved the colony from imminent collapse. From all over Brazil, as well as from Portugal, thousands of immigrants came to the mines in an early \"gold rush\".{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe [[Kingdom of Spain|Spanish]] tried to prevent Portuguese expansion northwest, west, southwest and southeast into the territory that belonged to them according to the 1494 [[Treaty of Tordesillas]] division of the [[New World]] of [[Americas|The Americas]] by the [[Bishop of Rome|Bishop and Pope of Rome]], [[Pope Alexander VI]] (1431-1503, reigned 1492-1503) and succeeded in conquering the ''Banda Oriental'' region in 1777. However, this was in vain as the [[First Treaty of San Ildefonso|Treaty of San Ildefonso]], signed in the same year, confirmed Portuguese sovereignty over all lands proceeding from its territorial expansion, thus creating most of the current Brazilian southeastern border.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nDuring the [[Invasion of Portugal (1807)|French invasion of Portugal]], by Emperor [[Napoleon Bonaparte|Napoleon I]] in 1807, the Portuguese royal family [[House of Braganza]] fled across the [[Atlantic Ocean]] with the help of the British [[Royal Navy]] to Brazil, establishing [[Rio de Janeiro]] as the de facto capital of Portugal and Brazil and the [[Portuguese Empire]] during the ensuing worldwide [[Napoleonic Wars]] (1803-1815).  This had the side effect of soon creating within Brazil, many of the institutions required to exist as an independent state; most importantly, it freed Brazil to trade with other nations at will.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nAfter Napoleon's Imperial French army was finally defeated at [[Battle of Waterloo|Waterloo]] in June 1815, in order to maintain the capital in Brazil and allay Brazilian fears of being returned to colonial status, [[King John VI of Portugal]] raised the [[de jure]] status of Brazil to an equal, integral part of a new status in a [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil, and the Algarves]], rather than a mere colony, a status which it enjoyed for the next seven years, sending his son, Dom [[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro]] as prince regent.\n\n==Path to independence==\n===Portuguese ''Cortes''===\n[[File:Portuguese Cortes 1822.jpg|left|thumb|200px|The Portuguese ''Cortes'']]\nIn 1820 the [[Liberal Revolution of 1820|Constitutionalist Revolution]] erupted in [[Portugal]]. The movement initiated by the liberal constitutionalists resulted in the meeting of the ''[[Constituent Cortes of 1820|Cortes]]'' (or [[Constituent Assembly]]), that would have to create the kingdom's first [[constitution]].<ref>Lustosa, p.97</ref><ref>Armitage. p.36</ref> The ''Cortes'' at the same time demanded the return of King [[Don (honorific)|Dom]] [[John VI of Portugal|John VI]], who had been living in [[Brazil]] since 1808, who elevated Brazil to a kingdom as part of the [[United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves]] in 1815 and who nominated his son and heir prince Dom [[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro]] as [[regent]], to govern Brazil in his place on 7 March 1821.<ref>Lustosa, p.106</ref><ref>Armitage. p. 38</ref> The king left for Europe on 26 April, while Dom Pedro remained in Brazil governing it with the aid of the ministers of the Kingdom (Interior) and Foreign Affairs, [[Ministry of Defence (Brazil)|of War, of Navy]] and [[Ministry of Finance (Brazil)|of Finance]].<ref>Lustosa, pp. 109\u201310</ref><ref>Armitage. p. 41</ref>\n\nThe Portuguese military officers headquartered in Brazil were completely sympathetic to the Constitutionalist movement in Portugal.<ref>Lustosa, p. 112</ref> The main leader of the Portuguese officers, General [[Jorge de Avilez Zuzarte de Sousa Tavares]] forced the prince to dismiss and banish from the country the ministers of Kingdom and Finance. Both were loyal allies of Pedro, who had become a pawn in the hands of the military.<ref>Lustosa, pp. 113\u201314</ref> The humiliation suffered by the prince, who swore he would never yield to the pressure of the military again, would have a decisive influence on his abdication ten years later.<ref>Lustosa, p. 114</ref> Meanwhile, on 30 September 1821, the ''Cortes'' approved a decree that subordinated the governments of the [[Brazilian provinces]] directly to Portugal. Prince Pedro became for all purposes only the governor of the [[Rio de Janeiro Province]].<ref name=\"Lustosa, p.117\">Lustosa, p. 117</ref><ref>Armitage. pp. 43\u201344</ref> Other decrees that came after ordered his return to Europe and also extinguished the judicial courts created by Jo\u00e3o VI in 1808.<ref name=\"Lustosa, p.119\">Lustosa, p.119</ref><ref>Armitage. pp. 48\u201351</ref>\n\nDissatisfaction over the ''Cortes'' measures among most residents in Brazil (both Brazilian-born and Portuguese-born) rose to a point that it soon became publicly known.<ref name=\"Lustosa, p.117\"/> Two groups that opposed the ''Cortes''' actions to gradually undermine the Brazilian sovereignty appeared: Liberals led by [[Joaquim Gon\u00e7alves Ledo]] (which had the support of the [[Freemason]]s) and the Bonifacians led by [[Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio de Andrada e Silva|Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio de Andrada]]. Both factions had nothing in common in their goals for Brazil, with the sole exception of their desire to keep the country united with Portugal as a sovereign monarchy.<ref>Di\u00e9gues, p. 70</ref>\n\n===Avilez rebellion===\n[[File:Pedro I of Brazil and Avilez.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Prince Pedro (right) orders Portuguese officer [[Jorge de Avilez Zuzarte de Sousa Tavares|Jorge de Avilez]] (left) to return to Portugal after his failed rebellion, 8 February 1822. [[Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio de Andrada e Silva|Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio]] (in civilian clothes) can be seen next to the prince.]]\nThe Portuguese deputies of the ''Cortes'' showed no respect towards the prince and openly mocked him.<ref>Lustosa, p.120</ref> And so the loyalty that Pedro had shown towards the ''Cortes'' gradually shifted to the Brazilian cause.<ref name=\"Lustosa, p.119\"/> His wife, princess [[Maria Leopoldina of Austria|Leopoldina of Habsburg]], favoured the Brazilian side and encouraged him to remain in the country<ref>Lustosa, pp. 121\u201322</ref> while the Liberals and Bonifacians made open representations. Pedro's reply came on 9 January 1822, who, according to newspapers, spoke: \"As it is for the good of all and for the nation's general happiness, I am ready: Tell the people that I will stay\".<ref>Lustosa, pp. 123-24</ref>\n\nAfter Pedro's decision to defy the ''Cortes'', around 2,000 men led by Jorge Avilez rioted before concentrating on mount Castelo, which was soon surrounded by 10,000 armed Brazilians, led by the [[Rio de Janeiro State Military Police|Royal Police Guard]].<ref>Lustosa, pp. 132\u201334</ref> Dom Pedro then \"dismissed\" the Portuguese commanding general and ordered him to remove his soldiers across the bay to [[Niter\u00f3i]], where they would await transport to Portugal.<ref>Lustosa, p. 135</ref>\n\nJose Bonif\u00e1cio was nominated minister of Kingdom and Foreign Affairs on 18 January 1822.<ref>Lustosa, p. 138</ref> Bonif\u00e1cio soon established a fatherlike relationship with Pedro, who began to consider the experienced [[politician|statesman]] his greatest ally.<ref>Lustosa, p. 139</ref> Gon\u00e7alves Ledo and the liberals tried to minimize the close relationship between Bonif\u00e1cio and Pedro offering to the prince the title of Perpetual Defender of Brazil.<ref name=\"Lustosa, p.143\">Lustosa, p. 143</ref><ref name=\"Armitage. p.61\">Armitage. p. 61</ref> For the liberals, the meeting of a Constituent Assembly for Brazil was necessary, while the Bonifacians preferred that Pedro grant the constitution himself to avoid the possibility of similar anarchy to the one that occurred during the first years of the [[French Revolution]].<ref name=\"Lustosa, p.143\"/>\n\nThe prince acquiesced to the liberals\u2019 desires and signed a decree on 3 June 1822 calling for the election of the deputies that would gather in the [[Constituent assembly|Constituent and Legislative General Assembly]] in Brazil.<ref name=\"Armitage. p.61\"/><ref>Lustosa, p. 145</ref>\n\n===From united kingdom to independent empire===\n{{more citations needed|section|date=June 2017}}\n[[File:Independencia brasil 001.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Prince Pedro is surrounded by a cheering crowd in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] after giving the news of the Brazilian independence on 7 September 1822.]]\nPedro departed to [[S\u00e3o Paulo Province]] to secure the province's loyalty to the Brazilian cause. He reached its [[S\u00e3o Paulo|capital]] on 25 August and remained there until 5 September. While on his way back to Rio de Janeiro on 7 September he received mail from Jos\u00e9 Bonif\u00e1cio and his wife, Leopoldina.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} The letter told him that the ''Cortes'' had annulled all acts from the Bonif\u00e1cio cabinet, removed Pedro's remaining powers and ordered him to return to Portugal.  It was clear that independence was the only option left. Pedro turned to his companions that included his [[Presidential Guard Battalion (Brazil)|Guard of Honor]] and spoke: \"Friends, the Portuguese ''Cortes'' want to enslave and pursue us. From today on our relations are broken. No ties can unite us anymore\" and continued after he pulled out his blue-white armband that symbolized Portugal: \"Armbands off, soldiers. Hail to the independence, to freedom and to the separation of Brazil from Portugal!\" He unsheathed his sword affirming that \"For my blood, my honor, my God, I swear to give Brazil freedom,\" and later cried out: \"Brazilians, Independence or death!\". This event is remembered as \"[[Cry of Ipiranga]]\".<ref>Lustosa, pp. 150\u201353</ref>\n\nReturning to the city of [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] on the night of 7 September 1822, [[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro]] and his companions announced the news of Brazilian independence from Portugal. The Prince was received with great popular celebration and was called not only \"King of Brazil\", but also \"Emperor of Brazil\".<ref name=\"Vianna, p.408\">Vianna, p. 408</ref><ref>Lima (1997), p. 398</ref>\n\n[[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro]] returned to [[Rio de Janeiro]] on 14 September and in the following days the liberals had spread pamphlets (written by [[Joaquim Gon\u00e7alves Ledo]]) that suggested the idea that the Prince should be acclaimed [[Constitutional monarchy|Constitutional Emperor]].<ref name=\"Vianna, p.408\"/> On 17 September the President of the [[Municipal council|Municipal Chamber]] of Rio de Janeiro, Jos\u0117 Clemente Pereira, sent to the other Chambers of the country the news that the [[Acclamation]] would occur in the anniversary of Pedro on 12 October.<ref>Lustosa, p. 153</ref>\n[[File:Coroa\u00e7ao pedro I 001.jpg|right|thumb|240px|Coronation of Emperor Pedro I on December 1, 1822.]]\nThe official separation would only occur on 22 September 1822 in a letter written by Pedro to [[John VI of Portugal|Jo\u00e3o VI]]. In it, Pedro still calls himself Prince Regent and his father is considered the King of the independent Brazil.<ref>Lima (1997), p. 379</ref><ref>Vianna, p. 413</ref> On 12 October 1822, in the Field of Santana (later known as Field of the Acclamation) Prince Pedro was acclaimed Dom Pedro I, Constitutional Emperor and Perpetual Defender of Brazil. It was at the same time the beginning of Pedro's reign and also of the [[Empire of Brazil]].<ref>Vianna, pp. 417\u201318</ref> However, the Emperor made it clear that although he accepted the emperorship, if Jo\u00e3o VI returned to Brazil he would step down from the throne in favor of his father.<ref>Lima (1997), p. 404</ref>\n\nThe reason for the imperial title was that the title of king would symbolically mean a continuation of the Portuguese dynastic tradition and perhaps of the feared absolutism, while the title of emperor derived from popular acclamation as in [[Ancient Rome]] or at least reigning through popular sanction as in the case of Napoleon.<ref>Lima (1997), p.339</ref><ref>Barman (1999), p. 4; \"Some weeks later he was acclaimed emperor as Pedro I of Brazil. In the terminology of the period, the word 'empire' signifying a monarchy of unusually large size and resources (as in the case of Russia), and this designation avoided D. Pedro's usurping the title of 'king' from his father, Jo\u00e3o VI.\"</ref> On 1 December 1822, Pedro I was crowned and consecrated.<ref>Vianna, p. 418</ref>\n\n==War of Independence==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2017}}\n\n{{main|War of Independence of Brazil}}\n[[File:Entrada do Ex\u00e9rcito Libertador 1930.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Brazilian Army]] entering [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]] after the surrender of the Portuguese forces in 1823.]]\n\nBut in spite of these fine words, the new flag and the Acclamation of Pedro as Constitutional Emperor, the authority of the new regime only extended to Rio de Janeiro, S\u00e3o Paulo and the adjacent provinces. The rest of Brazil remained firmly under the control of Portuguese juntas and garrisons.  It would take a war to put the whole of Brazil under Pedro's control.  The fighting began with skirmishes between rival militias in 1822 and lasted until January 1824, when the last Portuguese garrisons and naval units surrendered or left the country.\n\nMeanwhile, the Imperial government had to create a regular [[Brazilian Army|Army]] and [[Brazilian Navy|Navy]].  Forced enlistment was widespread, extending to foreign immigrants, and Brazil made use of slaves in militias, as well as freeing slaves to enlist them in army and navy. The campaigns on land and sea covered the vast territories of [[Bahia]], [[Montevideo and Cisplatina]], Gr\u00e3o-Par\u00e1. [[Maranh\u00e3o]], [[Pernambuco]], [[Cear\u00e1]] and [[Piau\u00ed]].\n\nBy 1822, Brazilian forces were firmly in control of [[Rio de Janeiro]] and the central area of Brazil.  Loyal militias began insurrections in the aforementioned territories, but strong, and regularly reinforced Portuguese garrisons in the port cities of  [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]], [[Montevideo]], [[S\u00e3o Lu\u00eds, Maranh\u00e3o|S\u00e3o Lu\u00eds]] and [[Bel\u00e9m]] continued to dominate the adjacent areas and to pose the threat of a reconquest that the irregular Brazilian militias and [[guerrilla]] forces, which were loosely besieging them by land supported by newly created units of the Brazilian army, would be unable to prevent.\n\nFor the Brazilians, the answer to this stalemate was to seize control of the sea.  Eleven former Portuguese warships, great and small, had fallen into Brazilian hands in Rio de Janeiro and these formed the basis of a new navy. The problem was manpower: the crews of these ships were largely Portuguese who were openly mutinous, and although many Portuguese naval officers had declared allegiance to Brazil their loyalty could not be relied on.  The Brazilian Government solved the problem by recruiting 50 officers and 500 seamen in secret in London and Liverpool, many of them veterans of the Napoleonic Wars, and appointed [[Thomas Cochrane, 10th Earl of Dundonald|Thomas Cochrane]] as commander-in-chief.<ref>Brian Vale 'Independence or Death: British Sailors and Brazilian Independence' I B Tauris, 1995</ref>\nOn 1 April 1823, a Brazilian squadron of 6 ships sailed for Bahia.  After an initial disappointing engagement with a superior Portuguese fleet, Cochrane blockaded Salvador.  Deprived now of supplies and reinforcements by sea and besieged by the Brazilian army on land, on 2 July the Portuguese forces abandoned Bahia in a convoy of 90 ships.  Leaving the frigate \u2018Niteroi\u2019 under Captain John Taylor to harry them to the coasts of Europe, Cochrane then sailed north to S\u00e3o Lu\u00eds (Maranh\u00e3o).  There he tricked the Portuguese garrison into evacuating Maranh\u00e3o by pretending that a huge Brazilian fleet and army were over the  horizon.  He then sent Captain John Pascoe Grenfell to play the same trick on the Portuguese in Bel\u00e9m do Par\u00e1 at the mouth of the Amazon.<ref>Brian Vale 'The Audacious Admiral Cochrane; The True Life of a Naval Legend',  Conway, 2004</ref>  By November 1823, the whole of the north of Brazil was under Brazilian control, and the following month, the demoralized Portuguese also evacuated Montevideo and the Cisplatine Province.  By 1824, Brazil was free of all enemy troops and was \u2018de facto\u2019 independent.<ref>Vale</ref>\n\nThere are still today no reliable [[statistics]]<ref>{{in lang|pt}} [[:pt:Laurentino Gomes|Laurentino Gomes]] [[1822 (book)|''1822'']] Nova Fronteira, Brasil 2010 {{ISBN|85-209-2409-3}} Chapter 10, p. 163</ref> related to the numbers of, for example, the total of the war casualties. However based upon historical registration and contemporary reports of some battles of this war as well as upon the admitted numbers in similar fights that happened in these times around the globe, and considering how long the Brazilian independence war lasted (22 months), estimates of all killed in action on both sides are placed from around 5,700 to 6,200.\n\n===In Pernambuco===\n* [[Siege of Recife]]\n\n===In Piau\u00ed and Maranh\u00e3o===\n* [[Battle of Jenipapo]]\n* [[Siege of Caxias]]\n\n===In Gr\u00e3o-Par\u00e1===\n* [[Siege of Bel\u00e9m]]\n\n===In Bahia===\n* [[Battle of Piraj\u00e1]]\n* [[Battle of Itaparica]]\n* [[Battle of 4 May]]\n* [[Siege of Salvador]]\n\n===In Cisplatina===\n* [[Siege of Montevideo (1823)]]\n\n==Peace treaty and aftermath==\nThe last Portuguese soldiers left Brazil in 1824.  A peace treaty recognizing Brazil's independence was drafted in summer 1825, and signed by Brazil and Portugal that autumn.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Brazil}}\n* [[Empire of Brazil]]\n* [[Colonial Brazil]]\n* [[Cry of Ipiranga]]\n* [[History of Brazil]]\n* [[Treaty of Rio de Janeiro (1825)]]\n* [[Independence Day (Brazil)]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* Gomes, Laurentino, ''[[1822 (book)|1822]]''<!-- ISSN/ISBN, publisher, year of publication needed -->\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=25em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* Armitage, John. ''Hist\u00f3ria do Brasil''. Belo Horizonte: Itatiaia, 1981. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Barman, Roderick J. ''Citizen Emperor: Pedro II and the Making of Brazil, 1825\u20131891.'' Stanford: Stanford University Press, 1999. {{in lang|en}}\n* Di\u00e9gues, Fernando. ''A revolu\u00e7\u00e3o bras\u00edlica''. Rio de Janeiro: Objetiva, 2004. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Dolhnikoff, Miriam. ''Pacto imperial: origens do federalismo no Brasil do s\u00e9culo XIX''. S\u00e3o Paulo: Globo, 2005. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Gomes, Laurentino. [[1822 (book)|''1822'']]. Nova Fronteira, 2010. {{ISBN|85-209-2409-3}} {{in lang|pt}}\n* Holanda, S\u00e9rgio Buarque de. ''O Brasil Mon\u00e1rquico: o processo de emancipa\u00e7\u00e3o''. 4. ed. S\u00e3o Paulo: Difus\u00e3o Europ\u00e9ia do Livro, 1976. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Lima, Manuel de Oliveira. ''O movimento da independ\u00eancia''. 6. ed. Rio de Janeiro: Topbooks, 1997. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Lustosa, Isabel. ''D. Pedro I''. S\u00e3o Paulo: Companhia das Letras, 2007. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Vainfas, Ronaldo. ''Dicion\u00e1rio do Brasil Imperial''. Rio de Janeiro: Objetiva, 2002. {{in lang|pt}}\n* Vianna, H\u00e9lio. ''Hist\u00f3ria do Brasil: per\u00edodo colonial, monarquia e rep\u00fablica''. 15. ed. S\u00e3o Paulo: Melhoramentos, 1994. {{in lang|pt}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n{{Brazil topics}}\n\n[[Category:1820s conflicts]]\n[[Category:Empire of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Military history of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Latin American wars of independence]]\n[[Category:1822 in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Separatism in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Separatism in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Brazil]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Portugal]]\n[[Category:Wars of independence]]\n[[Category:Brazil\u2013Portugal relations]]\n[[Category:1822 in international relations]]\n[[Category:Pedro I of Brazil]]\n\n[[it:Impero del Brasile#Indipendenza brasiliana]]\n", "name_user": "187.161.194.245", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independence_of_Brazil"}
{"title_page": "Mahnaz Afshar", "text_new": "{{short description|Iranian actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{no footnotes|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mahnaz Afshar\n| image              = Mahnaz Afshar 20180209 03.jpg\n| caption            = Afshar in 2018\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1977|6|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Esfahan]], [[Iran]]\n| othername          = \n| occupation         = [[Actress]]\n| yearsactive        = 1998\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Mohammad Yasin Ramin<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20171210160847/http://www.soozheha.org/afshar-mother-father-daughter/ Mahnaz Afshar and her mother in law, father in law and daughter]</ref>\n\n|2014|2019|reason=divorced}}\n| children           = Liana Ramin\n| influences         = \n| influenced         = \n| website            = \n}}\n'''Mahnaz Afshar''' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u0647\u0646\u0627\u0632 \u0627\u0641\u0634\u0627\u0631}}; born 11 June 1978) is an [[Iran]]ian actress who has been active since 1998 with acting in [[Iranian cinema|cinema]] and television serie.\n\n==Life and career==\nShe graduated in natural science in high school. After graduation, one of her relatives who was the Theater Affairs Assistant in \"Soureh\" college introduced her to \"Hannaneh\" Art institute. Having studied video edition in the following years, she participated in assembly job of \"Ket\u0101b-e Avval\" training materials, directed by [[Dariush Mehrjui]].\n\nLater on, she was invited by [[Shamsi Fazlollahi]] to act in a TV series called Gomshodeh (Lost) directed by Masoud Navaii, making her first official play in TV industry. Her professional career continued by acting in a movie called \"Doostam\" (Friends) directed by [[Abdollah Eskandari]]. The film, however, was not released in movie theaters due to complications with the authorities regarding the story and morals of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmmovement.com/filmcatalog/index.asp?MerchandiseID=92|title=MEN AT WORK - Buy Foreign Film DVDs - Watch Indie Films Online - Purchase Foreign Films - Stream Indie Films|website=www.filmmovement.com}}</ref>\n\nHer first official appearance as an actress in the cinema industry debuted in a work called \"Shour-e Eshgh\" (Passion of Love), which received positive reviews by audience and critics of the time. Having gained substantial fame for her act, she later appeared in \"Atash-bas\" (Ceasefire), a major hit, and \"Salad-e Fasl\" (Season Salad).\n\nAfshar is one of the judges of ''[[Persia's Got Talent]]'', a franchise of the British talent show ''[[Got Talent]]'', which is aired on [[MBC Persia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Has Iran's award-winning actress left Iran to escape prosecution? |first= Rohollah|last= Faghihi |url= https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/iranian-artist-becomes-controversy-between-iran-and-saudia.html |work= Al-Monitor|access-date=29 January 2020|publication-date=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Judging Iranian actress in a remake, Los Angeles + Video |url= https://www.mbs.news/2019/11/judging-iranian-actress-in-a-remake-los-angeles-video.html |publisher= mbs.news |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Director\n! Role\n|-\n| 1999\n| Shirha-ye-javan (The Young Lions)\n| Mohsen Mohseni Nasab\n|\n|- \n| 1999\n| Doostan (Friends)\n| Ali Shah Hatami\n|\n|- \n| 2000\n| Shoor-e eshgh (The Passion of Love)\n| Nader Moghaddas\n|\n|- \n| 2000\n| Khakestary (Gray)\n| \n| Bita\n|- \n| 2001\n| Negin (Gem)\n|\n| Neda\n|- \n| 2002\n| Zahr-e asal (The Poison of Honey)\n|\n|\n|- \n| 2002\n| Dokhtary dar ghafas (The Girl in the Cage)\n|\n|\n|- \n| 2003\n| Koma (Coma)\n|\n|\n|- \n| 2003\n| Sizdah gorbeh rooy-e shirvani  (13 Cats on the Roof)\n|\n|\n|- \n| 2004\n| Salad-e fasl (Season's Salad)\n| [[Fereydoun Jeyrani]]\n| Mehr Angiz\n|- \n| 2005\n| Kargaran mashghool e karand (Men at Work)\n| Mani Haghighi\n| Sahar  \n|- \n| 2005\n| Che kasi amir ra kosht?  (Who Murdered Amir?)\n| Mehdi Karampour\n| Marjan\n|- \n| 2005\n| Taleh (Trap)\n| Sirous Alvand \n|\n|- \n| 2005\n| Akvarium  (Aquarium)\n| [[Iraj Ghaderi]]\n|\n|- \n| 2006\n| Atash bas ([[Cease Fire (2006 film)|Cease Fire]])\n| [[Tahmineh Milani]]\n| Sayeh\n|- \n| 2006\n| Mohakemeh (The Trial)\n|\n|\n|- \n| 2006\n| Raees (The Boss)\n| [[Masoud Kimiai]]\n| Tala\n|- \n| 2007\n| Kalagh par \n|\n|\n|- \n| 2007\n| Tasvi-eh hesab (Pay Back)\n| [[Tahmineh Milani]]\n| Sara\n|- \n| 2007\n| Enekas (Reflection)\n|\n|\n|- \n| 2008\n| Shabane rooz\n| \n|\n|- \n| 2008\n| [[Invitation (Davat) (2008 Film)|Davat (Invitation)]]\n| [[Ebrahim Hatamikia]]\n| Shaida\n|- \n| 2008\n| Shirin\n| [[Abbas Kiarostami]]\n| Woman in audience\n|- \n| 2008\n| Poopak & mash mashal-lah\n| Farzad Motamen\n| Poopak\n|- \n| 2009\n| Emshab shab-e mahtab-e \n| Hadi Karimi\n| Sahar\n|- \n| 2009\n| Khatereh (Memory)\n| Nader Tarighat\n|\n|- \n| 2009\n| pesar-e adam, dokhtar-e hav-va (Eve's daughter, Adam's son)\n| Rambod Javan\n| Mina\n|- \n| 2009\n| tabagheh sev-vom (The third floor)\n| Bijan Mirbagheri\n|\n|- \n| 2010\n| Pazel (Puzzle) (Gheseye Pariya)\n| fereydoun Jeyrani\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| Barf rooye kajha (snow on pine trees)\n|[[Peyman Moaadi]]\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ye asheghaneye sadeh (A Simple Love story)\n| Saman Moghadam\n| Gandom\n|-\n| 2011\n| Pole Choobi ([[The Wooden Bridge|Wooden Bridge]])\n| Mehdi Karampour\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Felicity Land]]'' (Sa-adat abad)\n|Maziar Miri\n|Laleh\n|-\n| 2012\n| From Tehran to Paradise\n| \n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| Che khobe bargashti\n| [[Dariush Mehrjui]]\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Kolah Ghermezi 92''\n| [[Iraj Tahmasb]]\n| Herself\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Metropole''\n| [[Masoud Kimiai]]\n| Khatoon\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Biganeh''\n| Bahram Tavakoli\n| Sepideh\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Eshgh Tatil Nist''\n| [[Bijan Birang]]\n| Nafas\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Delam Mikhad'' (I Want)\n| Bahman Farman Ara\n| \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Moalem'' (Teacher)\n| Naser Saeidaf\n| \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Nahange Abar'' (Sperm Whale)\n| Saman Moghadam\n| Rouya\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Khane e Dar Khiaban 41'' (The House on the 41st Street)\n| Hamidreza Ghorbani\n| \n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Nahange Abar 2'' (Sperm Whale 2)\n| Saman Moghadam\n| Rouya\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Delighted (2016)|Delighted]]''\n| [[Abdolreza Kahani]]\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Woodpecker''\n| Behrouz Shoeibi\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Los Angeles - Tehran''\n| Tina Pakravan\n| Ayda\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Agitation''\n| Fereydoun Jeyrani\n| Darya\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Suddenly the tree''\n| Safi Yazdanian\n| Mahtab\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Ghasam'' (swear)\n| [[Mohsen Tanabandeh]]\n| Razia\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''New Moon Hotel''\n| Takefumi Tsutsui\n| Noushin\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.instagram.com/mahnaz_afshar/ Mahnaz Afshar] On [[Instagram]]\n{{commons cat}}\n*{{IMDb name}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Afshar, Mahnaz}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Iranian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Iranian female models]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Iranian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Tehran]]\n\n[[Category:Crystal Simorgh for Best Supporting Actress winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Iranian actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{no footnotes|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Mahnaz Afshar\n| image                   = Mahnaz Afshar 20180209 03.jpg\n| caption                 = Afshar in 2018\n| birth_name              = \n| birth_date              = {{birth date and age|1977|6|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place             = [[Tehran]], [[Iran]]\n| othername               = \n| occupation              = [[Actress]]\n| yearsactive             = 1998\u2013present\n| spouse                  = {{marriage|Mohammad Yasin Ramin<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20171210160847/http://www.soozheha.org/afshar-mother-father-daughter/ Mahnaz Afshar and her mother in law, father in law and daughter]</ref>\n\n|2014|2019|reason=divorced}}\n| children                = Liana Ramin\n| influences              = \n| influenced              = \n| website                 = \n}}\n'''Mahnaz Afshar''' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u0647\u0646\u0627\u0632 \u0627\u0641\u0634\u0627\u0631}}; born 11 June 1978) is an [[Iran]]ian actress who has been active since 1998 with acting in [[Iranian cinema|cinema]] and television series.\n\n==Life and career==\nShe graduated in natural science in high school. After graduation, one of her relatives who was the Theater Affairs Assistant in \"Soureh\" college introduced her to \"Hannaneh\" Art institute. Having studied video edition in the following years, she participated in assembly job of \"Ket\u0101b-e Avval\" training materials, directed by [[Dariush Mehrjui]].\n\nLater on, she was invited by [[Shamsi Fazlollahi]] to act in a TV series called Gomshodeh (Lost) directed by Masoud Navaii, making her first official play in TV industry. Her professional career continued by acting in a movie called \"Doostam\" (Friends) directed by [[Abdollah Eskandari]]. The film, however, was not released in movie theaters due to complications with the authorities regarding the story and morals of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmmovement.com/filmcatalog/index.asp?MerchandiseID=92|title=MEN AT WORK - Buy Foreign Film DVDs - Watch Indie Films Online - Purchase Foreign Films - Stream Indie Films|website=www.filmmovement.com}}</ref>\n\nHer first official appearance as an actress in the cinema industry debuted in a work called \"Shour-e Eshgh\" (Passion of Love), which received positive reviews by audience and critics of the time. Having gained substantial fame for her act, she later appeared in \"Atash-bas\" (Ceasefire), a major hit, and \"Salad-e Fasl\" (Season Salad).\n\nAfshar is one of the judges of ''[[Persia's Got Talent]]'', a franchise of the British talent show ''[[Got Talent]]'', which is aired on [[MBC Persia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Has Iran's award-winning actress left Iran to escape prosecution? |first= Rohollah|last= Faghihi |url= https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/iranian-artist-becomes-controversy-between-iran-and-saudia.html |work= Al-Monitor|access-date=29 January 2020|publication-date=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Judging Iranian actress in a remake, Los Angeles + Video |url= https://www.mbs.news/2019/11/judging-iranian-actress-in-a-remake-los-angeles-video.html |publisher= mbs.news |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Director\n! Role\n|-\n| 1999\n| Shirha-ye-javan (The Young Lions)\n| Mohsen Mohseni Nasab\n|\n|- \n| 1999\n| Doostan (Friends)\n| Ali Shah Hatami\n|\n|- \n| 2000\n| Shoor-e eshgh (The Passion of Love)\n| Nader Moghaddas\n|\n|- \n| 2000\n| Khakestary (Gray)\n| \n| Bita\n|- \n| 2001\n| Negin (Gem)\n|\n| Neda\n|- \n| 2002\n| Zahr-e asal (The Poison of Honey)\n|\n|\n|- \n| 2002\n| Dokhtary dar ghafas (The Girl in the Cage)\n|\n|\n|- \n| 2003\n| Koma (Coma)\n|\n|\n|- \n| 2003\n| Sizdah gorbeh rooy-e shirvani  (13 Cats on the Roof)\n|\n|\n|- \n| 2004\n| Salad-e fasl (Season's Salad)\n| [[Fereydoun Jeyrani]]\n| Mehr Angiz\n|- \n| 2005\n| Kargaran mashghool e karand (Men at Work)\n| Mani Haghighi\n| Sahar  \n|- \n| 2005\n| Che kasi amir ra kosht?  (Who Murdered Amir?)\n| Mehdi Karampour\n| Marjan\n|- \n| 2005\n| Taleh (Trap)\n| Sirous Alvand \n|\n|- \n| 2005\n| Akvarium  (Aquarium)\n| [[Iraj Ghaderi]]\n|\n|- \n| 2006\n| Atash bas ([[Cease Fire (2006 film)|Cease Fire]])\n| [[Tahmineh Milani]]\n| Sayeh\n|- \n| 2006\n| Mohakemeh (The Trial)\n|\n|\n|- \n| 2006\n| Raees (The Boss)\n| [[Masoud Kimiai]]\n| Tala\n|- \n| 2007\n| Kalagh par \n|\n|\n|- \n| 2007\n| Tasvi-eh hesab (Pay Back)\n| [[Tahmineh Milani]]\n| Sara\n|- \n| 2007\n| Enekas (Reflection)\n|\n|\n|- \n| 2008\n| Shabane rooz\n| \n|\n|- \n| 2008\n| [[Invitation (Davat) (2008 Film)|Davat (Invitation)]]\n| [[Ebrahim Hatamikia]]\n| Shaida\n|- \n| 2008\n| Shirin\n| [[Abbas Kiarostami]]\n| Woman in audience\n|- \n| 2008\n| Poopak & mash mashal-lah\n| Farzad Motamen\n| Poopak\n|- \n| 2009\n| Emshab shab-e mahtab-e \n| Hadi Karimi\n| Sahar\n|- \n| 2009\n| Khatereh (Memory)\n| Nader Tarighat\n|\n|- \n| 2009\n| pesar-e adam, dokhtar-e hav-va (Eve's daughter, Adam's son)\n| Rambod Javan\n| Mina\n|- \n| 2009\n| tabagheh sev-vom (The third floor)\n| Bijan Mirbagheri\n|\n|- \n| 2010\n| Pazel (Puzzle) (Gheseye Pariya)\n| fereydoun Jeyrani\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| Barf rooye kajha (snow on pine trees)\n|[[Peyman Moaadi]]\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ye asheghaneye sadeh (A Simple Love story)\n| Saman Moghadam\n| Gandom\n|-\n| 2011\n| Pole Choobi ([[The Wooden Bridge|Wooden Bridge]])\n| Mehdi Karampour\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Felicity Land]]'' (Sa-adat abad)\n|Maziar Miri\n|Laleh\n|-\n| 2012\n| From Tehran to Paradise\n| \n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| Che khobe bargashti\n| [[Dariush Mehrjui]]\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Kolah Ghermezi 92''\n| [[Iraj Tahmasb]]\n| Herself\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Metropole''\n| [[Masoud Kimiai]]\n| Khatoon\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Biganeh''\n| Bahram Tavakoli\n| Sepideh\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Eshgh Tatil Nist''\n| [[Bijan Birang]]\n| Nafas\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Delam Mikhad'' (I Want)\n| Bahman Farman Ara\n| \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Moalem'' (Teacher)\n| Naser Saeidaf\n| \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Nahange Abar'' (Sperm Whale)\n| Saman Moghadam\n| Rouya\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Khane e Dar Khiaban 41'' (The House on the 41st Street)\n| Hamidreza Ghorbani\n| \n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Nahange Abar 2'' (Sperm Whale 2)\n| Saman Moghadam\n| Rouya\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Delighted (2016)|Delighted]]''\n| [[Abdolreza Kahani]]\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Woodpecker''\n| Behrouz Shoeibi\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Los Angeles - Tehran''\n| Tina Pakravan\n| Ayda\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Agitation''\n| Fereydoun Jeyrani\n| Darya\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Suddenly the tree''\n| Safi Yazdanian\n| Mahtab\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Ghasam'' (swear)\n| [[Mohsen Tanabandeh]]\n| Razia\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''New Moon Hotel''\n| Takefumi Tsutsui\n| Noushin\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{